kami mengajakmu untuk menjadi relawan 16 film festival bali 2018!

16 film festival bali merupakan festival film untuk memperingati kampanye 16 hari anti kekerasan terhadap perempuan (16 days of activism against gender violence). festival film ini akan kembali diadakan pada 1â€“10 desember 2018. tunjukkan dukunganmu dengan berpartisipasi menjadi relawan!

rekrutmen ini terbuka untuk siapapun tanpa dibatasi oleh jenis kelamin, gender, umur, agama, ras, dan orientasi seksual. bagi yang berdomisili di bali, mari bergabung bersama kami untuk memperjuangkan lingkungan yang bebas dari kekerasan!

untuk mengisi formulir pendaftaran, silakan klik tautan tinyurl.com/16ffvolunteer

rekrutmen akan ditutup pada 17 november 2018 pukul 14:00 wita. pertemuan perdana akan diadakan pada 18 november petang.

what does â€œfeminismâ€ mean today? that is the question at the heart ofÂ we should all be feminists, a personal, eloquently-argued essayâ€”adapted from her much-viewed tedx talk of the same nameâ€”by chimamanda ngozi adichie.

text:
kami mengajakmu untuk menjadi relawan 16 film festival bali 2018!

16 film festival bali merupakan festival film untuk memperingati kampanye 16 hari anti kekerasan terhadap perempuan (16 days of activism against gender violence). festival film ini akan kembali diadakan pada 1â€“10 desember 2018. tunjukkan dukunganmu dengan berpartisipasi menjadi relawan!

rekrutmen ini terbuka untuk siapapun tanpa dibatasi oleh jenis kelamin, gender, umur, agama, ras, dan orientasi seksual. bagi yang berdomisili di bali, mari bergabung bersama kami untuk memperjuangkan lingkungan yang bebas dari kekerasan!

untuk mengisi formulir pendaftaran, silakan klik tautan tinyurl.com/16ffvolunteer

rekrutmen akan ditutup pada 17 november 2018 pukul 14:00 wita. pertemuan perdana akan diadakan pada 18 november petang.

#hearmetoo #metoo #gerakbersama #hapuskekerasanseksual #enambelasffest #enambelasffestbali

text: one life lesson i can teach my girls is friendship. i didn't have great friends growing up. everything people say about girls being nasty was true in my experience. my best friend on wednesday wouldn't be my best friend anymore by thursday morning. my leg hair was first pointed out to me in front of a crowd by someone i considered a friend. my #metoo happened because i was ditched and looking for my so called friends. i didn't have a constant. i didn't have someone i looked forward to seeing every day at school, at least until my sister was there with me. i learned to avoid girls and hang out in groups, i learned that i was probably wrong about what looked good on me, i didn't believe for a second that best friends actually existed. i was 18 when i finally met liz. i didn't even reach out to her or, if i remember correctly, talk to her until we'd met at both church and work. when you finally find your person, friendship is the most amazing gift. liz has seen me at my absolute best and absolute worst. i've held her hand through the toughest chapter of her life and nobody can tell me that was wrong. we can joke and we can share harsh truths. we can sit and watch tv or just sit and talk. i've gone to her house at 1 am when she needed me and she's dropped everything to be there for me. finding your person doesn't always happen when you're young. sometimes they come into your life much later and at a time when you needed them more than ever. and when you find your person, you'll know â¤ you'll know.

text: a huge shout out to my girls from summer camp. ğŸ’— i was recently reminded to listen to what iâ€™m needing to keep my mental health in check. my strength is not shown by placing myself in an environment that i know will cause a tremendous amount of stress, that will more than likely cause triggers just to prove a â€œpointâ€. my strength is shown by giving myself permission to honor what my mental health is needing. the scenario: thanksgiving is approaching, my favorite holiday. family gathers together in a house thatâ€™s way too small to accommodate the amount of people, but we cram ourselves inside, fill ourselves with turkey, squash, stuffing...and enough sweets to feed a small army. after we have consumed this amazing meal, we find ourselves in â€œfood comaâ€. some of us page through flyers for black friday, and others (me) take a midday snoozer. this may not be for some individuals, but for me...itâ€™s a holiday i look forward to all year! unfortunately, 2018 will be the second year that i wonâ€™t be attending. the reason? 16 film festival bali merupakan festival film untuk memperingati kampanye 16 hari anti kekerasan terhadap perempuan (16 days of activism against gender violence). festival film ini akan kembali diadakan pada 1â€“10 desember 2018. tunjukkan dukunganmu dengan berpartisipasi menjadi relawan!

rekrutmen ini terbuka untuk siapapun tanpa dibatasi oleh jenis kelamin, gender, umur, agama, ras, dan orientasi seksual. bagi yang berdomisili di bali, mari bergabung bersama kami untuk memperjuangkan lingkungan yang bebas dari kekerasan!

untuk mengisi formulir pendaftaran, silakan klik tautan tinyurl.com/16ffvolunteer

rekrutmen akan ditutup pada 17 november 2018 pukul 14:00 wita. pertemuan perdana akan diadakan pada 18 november 2018 petang.

#hearmetoo #metoo #gerakbersama #hapuskekerasanseksual #enambelasffest #enambelasffestbali

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think itâ€™s worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people donâ€™t necessarily know itâ€™s being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so itâ€™s worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that youâ€™re doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of peopleâ€™s personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldnâ€™t have seen, and couldnâ€™t have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, â€œwould work for anyoneâ€. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

itâ€™s an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing â€“ at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public â€“ our intimate family connections, our â€œlikesâ€, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole thatâ€™s expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

tweet_full:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
yesterday malin and naomi spent the whole day at the conference responsible organising rethink society at the swedish school of economics hanken @hankenofficial ğŸ‘Œ

on the first picture you find the crew for the workshop collaboration between goddess institute (professor emeritius jeff hearn and project leader charlotta niemistÃ¶) and ekvalita (malin). the second picture is a word cloud of all the participants first thoughts and reflection about #metoo
the rest of the pictures is the description of our workshop and malin talking ğŸ˜¬

our workshop was named post #metoo: what do we do, and after jeff and malins introduction to the theme,  the 50 participants worked in groups with the questions "what should we stop doing" "what should we continue to do" and "what should we start doing" with the frame of individuals and organisations. 
there was many good reflections and ideas that we hope the participants feelt inspired to bring with them into their contexts for change. our slides will be a available for all conference participants.

#responsibleorganising #postmetoo #metoo #responsibility #silenceculture #individuals #colletive #change #

text:
- bannon got it immediately. he believes in the whole andrew breitbart doctrine that politics is downstream from culture, so to change politics you need to change culture. and fashion trends are a useful proxy for that. trump is like a pair of uggs, or crocs, basically. so how do you get from people thinking â€˜ugh. totally uglyâ€™ to the moment when everyone is wearing them? that was the inflection point he was looking for.

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think itâ€™s worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people donâ€™t necessarily know itâ€™s being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so itâ€™s worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that youâ€™re doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of peopleâ€™s personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldnâ€™t have seen, and couldnâ€™t have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, â€œwould work for anyoneâ€. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean theyâ€™re mercenaries. theyâ€™ll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

itâ€™s an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing â€“ at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public â€“ our intimate family connections, our â€œlikesâ€, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole thatâ€™s expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
@richardafowler

wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

society, however, might not have the same viewpoint. had the roles been reversed, peopleâ€™s reactions to the speech would have been wholly different. how would it look if a sober guy takes advantage of a drunken girl who keeps passing out? does the world have enough pitchforks for such a mob? the sober guy would serve as irrefutable proof of â€œrape culture,â€ and the incapacitated girl would be the victim.

instead of outrage, schumer received praise. not only did people find her speech inspirational, they found it funny. she spends much of the time sex shaming the person she might have raped, and people thought it was both hilarious and brave. itâ€™s not hard to believe, weâ€™ve been laughing at men getting raped for a long time. take a look at movies like wedding crashers, and get him to the greek. rape is simply a comedic tool when itâ€™s placed upon men. more disturbingly, maybe society doesnâ€™t believe men can be raped at all.

text:
this was a serious business, it was actually backed by goldman sachs, but it crashed and went bankrupt because the gamers themselves who weren't cheating became enraged basically that these other people were doing, they put so much pressure on the gaming companies.

they put so much pressure on the video game companies, that they decided to basically ban gold-farming, which killed bannon's business, but it awakened him to the power of what he called "rootless white males" who spend all their time online. and five years later when bannon wound up at breitbart, he resolved to try and attract those people over to breitbart because he thought they could be radicalized in a kind of populist, nationalist way. and the way that bannon did that, the bridge between the angry abusive gamers and breitbart and pepe was milo yiannopoulous, who bannon discovered and hired to be breitbart's tech editor.

from the time i met him in 2011, he's had exactly the same politics. the same stuff you heard from trump, you saw on the campaign trail. what he was looking for was a vessel because nobody in republican washington believed in these kinds of ideas. the whole trend in the republican party was toward liberalizing immigration laws, passing comprehensive immigration reform. he was against it.

joshua green, author
devil's bargain: steve bannon, donald trump, and the storming of the presidency

- bannon got it immediately. he believes in the whole andrew breitbart doctrine that politics is downstream from culture, so to change politics you need to change culture. and fashion trends are a useful proxy for that. trump is like a pair of uggs, or crocs, basically. so how do you get from people thinking â€˜ugh. totally uglyâ€™ to the moment when everyone is wearing them? that was the inflection point he was looking for.

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think itâ€™s worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people donâ€™t necessarily know itâ€™s being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so itâ€™s worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that youâ€™re doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of peopleâ€™s personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldnâ€™t have seen, and couldnâ€™t have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, â€œwould work for anyoneâ€. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean theyâ€™re mercenaries. theyâ€™ll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

itâ€™s an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing â€“ at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public â€“ our intimate family connections, our â€œlikesâ€, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole thatâ€™s expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

text:
this was a serious business, it was actually backed by goldman sachs, but it crashed and went bankrupt because the gamers themselves who weren't cheating became enraged basically that these other people were doing, they put so much pressure on the gaming companies.

they put so much pressure on the video game companies, that they decided to basically ban gold-farming, which killed bannon's business, but it awakened him to the power of what he called "rootless white males" who spend all their time online. and five years later when bannon wound up at breitbart, he resolved to try and attract those people over to breitbart because he thought they could be radicalized in a kind of populist, nationalist way. and the way that bannon did that, the bridge between the angry abusive gamers and breitbart and pepe was milo yiannopoulous, who bannon discovered and hired to be breitbart's tech editor.

from the time i met him in 2011, he's had exactly the same politics. the same stuff you heard from trump, you saw on the campaign trail. what he was looking for was a vessel because nobody in republican washington believed in these kinds of ideas. the whole trend in the republican party was toward liberalizing immigration laws, passing comprehensive immigration reform. he was against it.

joshua green, author
devil's bargain: steve bannon, donald trump, and the storming of the presidency

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
#metoo: reflections .
itâ€™s been over a year since the #metoo campaign created a media storm.  as many women have since emphasised, the phrase was originally used by tarana burke, an african-american civil rights activist, over ten years ago.  since its usage was revisited in 2017, there have been many criticisms of the movementâ€™s lack of recognition of both its origins and degree of inclusivity.
.
predominately white, middle and upper class women in positions of privilege and power catalysed the success of the hashtag. yes, they faced discrimination and abuses of power that should be challenged at every level. but there is a feeling among many that the movement has been co-opted by white women who have subsequently taken the credit. women who made more â€˜acceptableâ€™ the discrimination that women of colour have long before been fighting against. it was then, that people started paying attention.
.
paulette barnes and diane williams were both african-american women who took their employees to court over sexual harassment claims. they won their cases and as a result paved the way for the supreme courtâ€™s ruling in 1986 that stated sexual harassment was a violation of the civil rights act. women of colour have fought to dismantle the interweaving structures of race and sexism for decades. it is the actions of communities with the least power that have made more possible the current landscape of feminism today. these actions cannot remain invisible and whitewashed.
.
what are your reflections on the #metoo movement?
.
.
.
.
.

repostby @belinda_vegan: "all use of animals for food, clothing, entertainment, pets or experimentation involves utilising animals against their will, and - in the vast majority of cases - involves their suffering and deaths. we are brought up to believe in our current society that we need to consume or make use of other animals but this is neither ethical nor necessary. instead, vegans choose to live a lifestyle that respects other animals as sentient individuals whose lives have meaning and do not consume, wear or use animal products or take part in activities which exploit animals. today, being vegan is easy, proven to be healthy and needn't cost more. 
_
being vegan is about living a lifestyle that does not cause suffering, harm or death to animals, and allowing animals to be free to choose the way they want to live. other animals are sentient beings like us, with their own needs, desires and interests. we now know that like us, they can experience a wide range of sensations and emotions such as happiness, pain, pleasure, fear, hunger, sadness, boredom, frustration or contentment. they are aware of the world and what happens to them matters to them. their lives have intrinsic value - they are not inferior beings nor just here as resources or tools for human use. discriminating against non-human animals or believing them to be inferior solely because they belong to a different species is known as speciesism and is as unscientific and unjust as racism or sexism. 
_

text:
i have many thoughts on #metoo â€“ why is the burden on women to constantly perform our trauma in order to be believed? why do we idealize women even as victims of gender violence, in our conception of the â€œperfect victimâ€ who is worthy of belief? when will we move from interrogating womenâ€™s silence (if you really were abused why didnâ€™t you speak up earlier...), to interrogating and dismantling the power imbalances that create this culture of silence? .
.
thankfully @sgwritersfest gave me a platform to share these thoughts alongside amazing women writers sarah churchwell and @annalizabakri . we had a full house on saturday night in the old parliament chamber, and it was poignant to discuss how to advance gender equality in a historically male space. i even got to read a new poem (that i wrote in my car at 1 am the night before) on girlhood and shame. .
.
kudos to rockstar moderator @anitakapoor who tethered the discussion to an asian context and kept the room rapt in conversation all the way till 10pm (we were supposed to end at 930pm!) lots of feels for this diverse sisterhood!! the project of feminism will only be over, when women are no longer predominantly defined by communal suffering, but instead are free to thrive. .
.
p.s. for the ten people who still listen to radio, iâ€™m on 938now with susan ng today (wednesday) at 9-10pm to discuss my work as a writer and advocate for social justice. tune in now for #moremandythoughts.
.
.
.
#womenwhowrite #swf2018 #singlit #socialjustice #feminism #feminist #equality

text:
lessons from the himalayas, day 8 (lobuche - ebc - gorakshep): you cannot move mountains; they will move you.
â€¢
last fall was defined by depression, anxiety, an unhealthy relationship, heartbreak, rage, low self-esteem, car accidents, ptsd, increasing stress and dissatisfaction at work, and #metoo. i had panic attacks in my sleep and an intensifying dark period in which i distanced myself from people and things i cared about.
â€¢
however, travel helped remind me of a greater world around me. i constantly found myself on a mountain or the highest hill i could find, guided by the universe to reach a higher place and state of being.
â€¢
from easter island to everest base camp, and many places in between, the past year has been an adventure rooted in healing. about becoming stronger mentally, emotionally, and physically. about prioritizing my wellness and happiness. about challenging and changing perceptions of self, failure, and success. about personal growth and climbing mountains, literally and figuratively.
â€¢
this is what i celebrated in the himalayas -- from rock bottom to the tallest mountains on earth. so much happens in a year, and for that, i am grateful.
â€¢

text:
another gorgeous find. i've seen this one hanging around on instagram, but oh, to have it in my hands. so pretty. each page is actually, literally a work of art. see that cover? every page inside is just like that: a gorgeous headshot of an incredible american woman.
ğŸ’ª
some of my favorites include carol kaye, bass player extraordinaire, who "could do anything and leave men in the dust"; lozen, warrior and prophet of the chihenne chiricahua apache, who helped save her people; ray eames, artist and designer, usually not recognized as an equal contributor to the eames design legacy (google "eames lounge chair") and yuri kochiyama, mother of six and peace activist who among other things, played an important role in the civil rights movement.
ğŸ’ª
i mean, we are talking about some seriously amazing women.  pair that with the unique and beautiful artwork and this is a stunning book. this is perfect for teens, but don't be afraid to read it to your younger ones, too!
.
.
.

text:
dear ladies,

no matter how much anyone tries to pull you down or pick you up, remember this, that you are your own source of energy and happiness.
your aura attracts energy and positivity from positive people. so be around people who makes you smile.
no matter how busy you are in you daily life, take out time for yourself, may you be a student, a home-maker, an entrepreneur, a mother, a father, a businessman, whatever you are, make time for yourself.
trust me, it's very important for a healthy lifestyle.
re-charge you body.
rejuvenate your soul.
re-energise your senses.
restore power in each cell.
and be your own reason for your happiness.
smile and spread smile.
.
.
Â©shwetha @shwetha_rishi

text:
her soul story is prepping for a big year ahead. our focus this month in her soul circle (our membership/community program) revolves around mindfulness and meditation. therefore, we are using this month to prep for the next year to come with mindfulness at the forefront of our planning process. you can be mindful in all aspects of your life, and for us, itâ€™s just as important to be mindful in our work life as it is our personal life. take a moment to reflect on an area in your life that could use some extra care in the mindfulness area. what can you do today to create greater intention in that area of your life? ğŸ™ğŸ»
try this to get you started:
1. slow down, take a deep inhale through your nose (count to 5) and then slowly exhale through your mouth. repeat if needed. 
2. decide on the area in your life that could benefit from increased mindfulness.
3. take a moment to create a clear and thoughtful intention regarding this area of your life. 
4. create 3 mindfulness practices for this area of your life. they should be easy and quick practices that are not hard to follow, but will help create a pattern of change.
.
.
.
.
.

text:
todayâ€™s #excellencewednesday spotlight goes to the incredible, tarana burke.
â€¢
â€¢
tarana burke is a civil rights activist who was the original founder of the "me too" movement. after working with survivors of sexual violence, she developed the nonprofit "just be" in 2003, which was an all-girls program for young black girls aged 12 to 18. in 2006, tarana founded the me too movement and began using the phrase "me too" to raise awareness of the pervasiveness of sexual abuse and assault in society. â€¢
â€¢

the phrase "me too" developed into a broader movement following the 2017 use of #metoo as a hashtag following the harvey weinstein sexual abuse allegations. on october 15, 2017, tarana was notified by her friends that the #metoo hashtag was being used online. she decided to be in service and shape the movement to make it about "empowermental empathy". time named her, among a group of other prominent female activists dubbed "the silence breakers", as the time person of the year for 2017. â€¢
â€¢

tarana received the 2018 prize for courage from the ridenhour prizes, which is awarded to individuals who demonstrate courageous defense of the public interest and passionate commitment to social justice, for popularizing the phrase â€œme tooâ€ as a way to empathize with sexual assault survivors more than a decade ago. she is currently the senior director at girls for gender equity. burke organizes workshops to help improve policies at schools, workplaces, and places of worship, and focuses on helping victims not blame themselves for sexual violence
â€¢
â€¢

they put so much pressure on the video game companies, that they decided to basically ban gold-farming, which killed bannon's business, but it awakened him to the power of what he called "rootless white males" who spend all their time online. and five years later when bannon wound up at breitbart, he resolved to try and attract those people over to breitbart because he thought they could be radicalized in a kind of populist, nationalist way. and the way that bannon did that, the bridge between the angry abusive gamers and breitbart and pepe was milo yiannopoulous, who bannon discovered and hired to be breitbart's tech editor.

from the time i met him in 2011, he's had exactly the same politics. the same stuff you heard from trump, you saw on the campaign trail. what he was looking for was a vessel because nobody in republican washington believed in these kinds of ideas. the whole trend in the republican party was toward liberalizing immigration laws, passing comprehensive immigration reform. he was against it.

joshua green, author
devil's bargain: steve bannon, donald trump, and the storming of the presidency

text:
this was a serious business, it was actually backed by goldman sachs, but it crashed and went bankrupt because the gamers themselves who weren't cheating became enraged basically that these other people were doing, they put so much pressure on the gaming companies.

they put so much pressure on the video game companies, that they decided to basically ban gold-farming, which killed bannon's business, but it awakened him to the power of what he called "rootless white males" who spend all their time online. and five years later when bannon wound up at breitbart, he resolved to try and attract those people over to breitbart because he thought they could be radicalized in a kind of populist, nationalist way. and the way that bannon did that, the bridge between the angry abusive gamers and breitbart and pepe was milo yiannopoulous, who bannon discovered and hired to be breitbart's tech editor.

from the time i met him in 2011, he's had exactly the same politics. the same stuff you heard from trump, you saw on the campaign trail. what he was looking for was a vessel because nobody in republican washington believed in these kinds of ideas. the whole trend in the republican party was toward liberalizing immigration laws, passing comprehensive immigration reform. he was against it.

joshua green, author
devil's bargain: steve bannon, donald trump, and the storming of the presidency

text: a true inspiration is someone who has struggled, fought through the pain and endured the darkness and still never lost faith. now, on the other side of pain is greatness, peace and strength beyond measure. this person is even more powerful when she loves herself and others in spite of her past transgressions. she sees the good and the light in others. she teaches them to love themselves, forgive themselves and discover their personal power and divine purpose. she watches as they believe in themselves, as they grow stronger from the inside out, more beautiful than ever... colored by their inner light and love. then, they become the inspiration to others because they have found their perfect essence... the one they were born with. and they will empower and share their strength and hope with others.... the cycle of healing and transformation continues ğŸ™ i am grateful for the journey... for the painful lessons as well as the beautiful ones. i am grateful for everyone who takes a chance on themselves and faces their fears. the door of self transformation swings inward. i am a personal trainer... this is what my job makes me feel every single day. #fitfam #wellness #yoga #friends #selflove #personaltrainer #mindfulness #metoo #believe #faith #love #bethechange

and most of you know that my mom chose my step dad over me, 2 and a half years ago.. she chose to stay with him after he admitted inappropriately touching me as a child.

text:
psssst, can i show you something we've been working on for a hot minute? come, gather round the fire, i want to share a story with you. leading into our second thru-hike of the #transcatalinatrail, so much had changed since the first time we did the trail after the 2016 election. i spent time in paris without the negative soundtrack that was rotting my brain and confidence here in the states, learned how to paddleboard, was diagnosed with diabetes, and i left a six-figure salary to join a startup only to leave the startup 95 days later without a backup plan. this time, i had nothing in my way except myself and my old stories. i had been playing with this concept of #hikingmyfeelings and was excited to work through some stuff on the trail.

i knew this trip was going to be a big deal just by deciding to attempt the trail again. i knew the timing was divinely guided and i wanted to capture every moment. i recorded a long entry before we even left for the trail, and then did one at every major milestone during the 40+ mile journey across the island.

the first hike was the start of my journey to love my body. before setting foot in that @rei dressing room in december 2016, i had done my research on the trail and had an idea of what to expect. with one simple question, "how did we get here?" and a gentle nudge, "how can we honor our inner athlete?" i had no idea what kind of adventure i was about to embark on.

full video coming soon! in the meantime, this month we kick off the @hikingmyfeelings #tcttraining group down here in san diego. if you're at all interested in hiking the tct, i'd love to see you one of the hikes coming up and answer any questions you may have about the group, the trail, or our plans for hiking the tct in 2019. we have some big things cooking and we're excited to share more soon. make sure you don't miss a beat, sign up for more info at hikingmyfeelings.com (link also in bio)

.

text:
this anonymous submission and the story behind it are a stark reminder that consent must be ongoing. just because you consent to one thing doesnâ€™t mean you consent to everything. here is the context behind this submission: he was my boyfriend, fresh out of boot camp for the military and as we were having sex, his family came home. i told him we needed to stop, that he needed to get off of me but he only held me tighter and said "it's okay, you just have to shut up" he then started going harder, more aggressive and i kept telling him to stop. he put his hand over my mouth and continued. ignoring my tears, muffling my cries until i laid there motionless and numb. all with his family in the next room.
.
.
.
.

text_retweet:
#repost @themissemily
.
.
.
on monday, october 29th, 2018, i shared an incredible experience with nearly 100 cast and crew at the kingston penitentiary. the pen closed in 2013 and has been open for limited tours in recent years.
.
when director jay middaugh suggested we try and get the pen for our upcoming hold back the river video shoot, i knew that meant i was going to have to actually find the courage to tour the property.  it had never interested me before.  it is a national historic site and a huge part of the history of kingston, but the idea of exposing myself to the energy in those buildings on the site made me feel sick.  we had two extensive tours of the grounds and buildings before we settled on october 29th as our filming date.  when the morning of the video shoot arrived, i felt different about the space.  i changed my mind on deciding to not just "get through" the day but to allow it to be an opportunity to bring in an abundance of positive and loving energy to a place that has been filled with negativity since it's opening in 1835.
.
i would like to thank the entire group of brave, passionate and positive human beings who committed themselves on october 29th to infiltrating new beautiful energy into a place of darkness.  some of the incredible participants shared their stories with me.  many were very personal and i am grateful they felt that this experience was an opportunity to do some healing and to gather as a group of women passionate about an important movement.
.
#metoo #metoomovement
.
the first step to fixing a problem is recognizing there's a problem.
the truth will set us free.
.
please click link in bio to watch the video, and donâ€™t forget to share!

text:
part 1:  everything changes...again
â€¢
itâ€™s the beginning of 2018, february 28. iâ€™m walking back to my car after a work function and iâ€™m followed by a drunk fellow coworker back to my car. over the next hour sexual assault becomes my reality, cornered in my car, only dark, empty streets to turn to. â€¢
i thought this part of my life was over. i stopped going to parties, i havenâ€™t touched alcohol since college...what had i done, how had i asked for this? why did my no mean nothing, my tears and pleas to stop unnoticed? â€¢
for a few months i stayed quite. i kept my problems to myself and i suffered the consequences, i relapsed into self harm. i couldnâ€™t let it go though, i had to do the thing that i had never done before, i had to do what scared me most. i had to tell my story and i had to be as loud as i could. i had to fight for myself, i had to remind myself that i mattered too. â€¢
#healing #metoo #stillfighting #standup #beyourownhero

text:
i looked at her,
and then i looked around like always.
something pinched me out.

it has always been like this,
with me, twirling through my ups & downs.
running to be understood & appreciated,
by different people in different places.

everyone's tired & messed up within themselves,
but they do manage to keep up their "best faces forward" in their different shelves.

i see, everyone is carrying their baggage,
so i fear that if i talk, i might add on to it.
so i bare mine, all to myself when they are gone,
in my corner where i sit.

for i know unloading it to an unknown will come at a cost,
but then when i search within to fight it out,
many of the times i feel so lost.

i try to be it all, 
i try to do it all,
from being the best daughter, friend or an ideal partner he treasures,
but they miss the chance to catch me,
when i go to my bottomless pit with no measure.

i wish i could tell them that it feels like being choked every minute.
every moment of which i let go,
when i give up what i want to make them happy,
even when it drives me to a new level low.

text:
are you an underdog? 
i love an underdog. the definition of an underdog is a competitor thought to have little chance of winning a fight or contest.lately i have been feeling like i should show my faith and love of jesus more publicly. yet i donâ€™t. i have always been a firm believer in that my love for jesus should be seen from afar and not spoken about. i live this, most relatively, with my boys. unfortunately, salvation is not something we can inherent. itâ€™s not like a family jewel that can be passed down generation to generation. therefore, i want them to know by example that mom loves jesus. i want them to see  thru me that they too can find peace. they are the first people to whom i pour into wether i like it or not.  this weekend was tough. i spoke to someone whom i love, in a way that i shouldâ€™ve never done. after talking to someone who has known pj squared ( pre-jesus jenny) i realized that itâ€™s ok to have these moments. we just canâ€™t stay there. i left that conversation astounded because he doesnâ€™t really know the jenny that i am now. he knows the old me. yet he said something that brought me so much reassurance. he saidâ€ your cup is so full, itâ€™s running over, youâ€™re pouring into othersâ€. to hear them say that shook me. he hasnâ€™t seen my love for christ but that day he heard it.  so today, i wanted to post this to help you find that same reassurance. in a world where we only show our highlights and wins. i wanted you guys to know that i struggle so much. i wanted to show my vulnerability and share that i struggle daily with my walk towards righteousness. i too fall short of his glory and i battle daily with thoughts of unworthiness and feelings that i am never going to be enough. i am my own underdog. i feel like iâ€™m never going to be a great mom, a great daughter, a great wife. i struggle in every aspect. physically, emotionally, spiritually. yet because of my faith, i can reassure myself that everything will be ok. this journey of life will always make you  feel like you canâ€™t win the battles but because we know the one who made us,  we can live reassured that the war has already been won. so today i make a public statement of #metoo. because i too

text:
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text:
i've watched the qspiracy since the start.

steve bannon left the wh august last year and q appeared the following october. do you believe in coincidences?

abusing and leaking presidential information to mislead the people and benefit the hijacked party of puppets is obviously just business as usual.

however - while doing this djt with the brave bunch known as gop has willingly opened a pussy wound that anyone around the world can easily contaminate. i like to call it meddlin' with presidental blessin'. i'm not the only one who knows this opportunity and messes with the bombastic patriots - may be russia or china or mbs or antifa or me, a tiny quarter pounder sitting on my bed.

the whole qshow seems like a vile roleplay but instead it has become the heart of the propaganda operation that joseph goebbels would have died for. it is obvious that stuff like pizzagateâ„¢ was testing for the 2016 election.

the accompanying memes go way beyond the propaganda of nsdap. social media companies are just helpless with the content and more or less fake accounts - there is no way they are going to risk their business by taking the responsibility.

there is absolutely no way that gop isn't aware of what is going on - after all cambridge analytica worked for ted cruz and john bolton. the whole thing is build on the same user data that bannon and the mercers reportedly got from cambridge analytica.

and here comes the best part. trumq is truly playing along with his tweets, gestures and words.

the bigger issue still is that requqlicans are willingly piggybacking this lunacy and abusing the faith of their fellow men while campaigning for the midterms. this is not just an insane national security risk - it's a leaking conspiracy and treason in plain sight.

a non

text:
"my name is daniel addison. i'm originally from brooklyn, raised on long island, and when i'm not at my regular day job i'm a volunteer mentor. .

when i was growing up there was violence all around me. i think the turning point was when i saw a young guy get shot in the street and the bullet barely missed me. that was when i said "enough". .
i got involved working with kids because i felt that i could use my experience as a focal point to educate them about gang violence, gun violence, bullying, etc. i also have a son of my own, and i think it's important for him and all young people to take advantage of the opportunities around them and do something better with their lives.
.

if i could offer one piece of advice to kids who are being abused: don't be scared to tell someone so they can intervene. it can be your parent, a teacher, or whoever, but definitely let someone know. you're not alone, and there are people who can help you." .
.

join us for a beautiful day celebrating women among the waves! 
40 surf sisters will gather from near and far to share waves in the morning before we meet for a delicious brunch at el manglar, a restaurant owned and run by all local costa rican women, located inside olas verdes resort in playa guiones. 
after brunch weâ€™ll get down to biz with @katherineterrell_  owner of @jeuxdevagues_ eco-friendly bikinis who will facilitate the panel discussion with @andreadiazsurfer and me. 
if you donâ€™t know andrea diaz, itâ€™s about time you did. and if you do, you know sheâ€™s a legend in costa rican surfing, a former roxy girl, an incredible surfer and surf instructor for @safari_surf_chicas, and a brilliant mother of three. and the best part is, she and i will be speaking at surf + brunch / nosara on meaningful issues of surfeminism, misogyny and #metoo in surf culture, surf colonialism and equity for women in surfing. 
tickets are halfway sold already, so be sure to grab yours before theyâ€™re gone. 
and, @beefree4 / @riseupshots and i will be filming a collaborative spoken word video based on my story â€˜wait your turnâ€™, which had some heads spinning in the surfing world earlier this year. there will be an opportunity for you to get involved in the video, as well! 
calling all sea-star mermaids, we canâ€™t wait to welcome you to surf + brunch / nosara, in just 17 days.

text:
we're joining in with #museum30 this month and today is 'reflection'. for todays museum 30 we're reflecting on the #metoo movement thatâ€™s shaped the past year. weâ€™ve created posthealing, an online community that encourages survivors of sexual, child, and domestic violence to heal through making and sharing art. taking the lead from postsecret, posthealing encourages the anonymous sharing of stories and experiences through multimedia in the hopes that art will help the creator heal â€˜postâ€™-violence, inspire others in similar situations to seek safety and reach healing, and educate victims and non-victims about the personal effects of the global problem of violence against women and girls. posthealing is a creative project started by girl museum in participating with and celebration of one billion rising, a global movement to end sexual violence. begun in 2013, the project underwent a strategic change of focus in 2018 to become more inclusive of various media types, gender identities, and modern social movements such as #metoo. head to https://www.girlmuseum.org/project/posthealing/ to see more.

text:
today, for #wcw, we are crushing on @alyraisman! thank you aly raisman for sharing your story and your thoughts about being a survivor of sexual abuse. aly encouraged the 900-person crowd at our shofar kick-off event last night to speak up, support each other and believe each other. 20 years of sexual abuse could have been prevented if someone would have believed and took seriously the first compliant of larry nassarâ€™s abuse in 1997. aly also warned us of â€œred flagsâ€ that might signal abuse is taking place in relationships around us, and she encouraged survivors to know that sexual abuse is not their fault, to be courageous in speaking up and to take self-care seriously.
.
just as aly sees speaking up about sexual abuse as her responsibility to do good, mjf sees the launch of shofar (safeguarding healthy families and relationships) as our responsibility to pursue justice (deuteronomy 16:20). mjf is launching this #shofarmke initiative in partnership with @sojournermke family peace center, @jewishfamilyservicesmke and @shalvachicago. please visitÂ https://www.milwaukeejewish.org/shofar/Â (link in bio) or text shofar to 51555 to get resources and support.
.

text:
let's jump into the deep water together, shall we?

i have a ove/hate relationship with #metoo. on one hand, it gives a platform and throws a spotlight on the fuckeries that women have been facing, whether she's an actress in hollywood or a cleaner in holiday inn, she's being heard out thanks to this social phenomenon that's taken over and invited many conversations. the other, it gives a disguise to these she-wolves who want nothing but to huff, puff and blow down a man's reputation with breaths of false allegations.

@oloni said this earlier, and it's so crazy but i really had no idea how crazy and warped this mindset is until she made me deep it (big pause). you get baby girl back from dinner, you were eating good and you're about to dine greater. you were flirting with each other from time; you dropped some hesitant bars about her seeing you a certain way (please see = game and bollocks) , she asked "what are you....what are you what are you so afraid of?" but then you get on your worst behaviour, try slip your hand to connect, feel the lips and talk the language, but she bats your hand away and says it's too much. you inhale the l, go home, eat some pound cake, then wake up to messages from her saying "why didn't u take all me last night then? ğŸ˜¡ğŸ˜ˆ". two things have been established. 1) this broad is crazy and 2) nothing was the same coz shes blocked now.

this is the kind of behaviour that gets a lot of males bagged on some fuckery. sexual frustration is one thing; you can deal wih that with a one meditation, some priya rai videos and the finest squirtings of palmer's cocoa butter. but what about the stark reality that there's a lot of women that walk around with this "no means no depending on my mood coz then it's yes" attitude, poisoning a lot of man drinking from that barrel? as i said on @thecommentsectionuk, forced sexual interaction, from harassment to out-and-out rape, isn't on. with that said...you you women that act like this when a man is tryna get it in have to really have a ted talk with yourselves. it's not as bad as falsifying rape claims, but toxic behaviours have to be stamped out once identified.

text:
he said â€œwe can be friends after this right?â€ ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
1 in 3 women have been victims of sexual assault, sexual harassment and in some cases sexual coercion. 
with the #metoo movement about i have taken time to process my own trauma from sexual abuse. i didnâ€™t want to be part of this statistic and i didnâ€™t want someone close to me to be apart of it either. this was something i was going to my grave with, i didnâ€™t want anyone to know. i am sharing this today because i know its not about me. i have taken myself out of the equation to look at the big picture. its about helping other women through their experiences i had to carry this burden for a while before i recently told someone close to me. i donâ€™t want you all to carry the burden like i did.  tell your story!! me telling my story and someone close to me telling me hers is the start to healing. ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
today i urge you if you are going through a hard time talk to someone, your best friend, a family member and if you have to.... a therapist (i am a huge advocate for talking to a therapist or just talking in general) there is no reason for you to hold things in let it bleed, and then let it go, its the start to something better. we are not our experiences! ğŸ™ğŸ¾ ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~ i know this sad story is before the holidays but i felt i should share it to remember the good things and not the bad

text:
just two more sessions of resilience for the resistance left. 
join us for this free online gathering to discuss how survivors of sexual assault and harassment can engage in activism work in a way that is sustainable. 
as survivors we can often overextend, overcommit, and over work ourselves. and the disclosures that have come along with the #metoo movement can often be re-traumatizing. 
in order to effect the change we want to see, we must stay resourced and resilient for the long game. letâ€™s gather to rest, reframe and gain tools that genuinely contribute to healthy self-care. 
canâ€™t make it live? signup and we will send you the replay. 
visit our calendar link in bio to view and signup for both sessions!

text:
good atfernoon friends!!! rise and grind!!! .
.
ever felt as though you are the only one going through your circumstances or your storm and no one can relate to you or even understands how you feel??.. i've been there.
.
.
when you put up this pretty facade not only for social media but for the world as though everything in your world is perfect... when inside you are truly a crumbling mess!! ever been stagnant and so paralyzed mentally & emotionally by things that have happened to you that the thought of healing or moving on is simply a distant thought in the wind??...its ok!!! .
.
my book live through it..is a testament of that very same thought pattern... pretending to be someone i wasn't ... when in reality i was still this broken little 9 year old girl still acting outward on everyone else what i felt inward!! .
.
but through every mistake, every action, everything that has happened .... i made a decision to survive and live through it !!! and so can you!! - by joining me on my journey through life you will find principles and applications that you can identity with and use in your own storms!!! .... we are more than conquers... we just have to live through it!!! .
make a decision today to no longer go through life operating in frustration, confusion, isolation and hurt!! head over to purchase your copy today ğŸ‘‡ğŸ¾ğŸ‘‡ğŸ¾ğŸ‘‡ğŸ¾
.
www.livethruit.com

text: dear friends. i miss you. i will always love you. ya know, a lot of people have been strange about me calling certain things out. regardless i need to say something. when i was working in the hospital witnessed a lot of weird stuff. was incredibly uncomfortable with the dehumanization, and not only that how the team treated each other. i called them nazis. i genuinely thought they were nazis. my dad had passed away, and i just kinda did not go back to work, because they were exploiting my pain a lot in there refused to allow that anymore. it was terrible and i know i'm better living; not allowing them to have any time in my life. it's about 4-5 months later, finally starting to feel semi ok, i even talk to the people i work with on humane levels, more than what i can say for the people of the lab. feeling ok, decided hey, maybe i misjudged them, maybe with all that is going on in the world i just called people nazis...i looked up their personal page. what is on their page. literal white supremacist, hate speech tattoos and lingo and guns and all around dead ass on with the original gut feeling of whoa pretty certain that's a nazi. little hospital midget hitler running around in the healthcare system. white ink, number 175. so understand, i'm not yelling nazi as something that isn't reality. i have proof. where the fuck do i report nazis is a different dilemma. lehigh valley no safe. america no safe. pretty certain i myself am done with white people. challenging initial reactions and beliefs is important for growth, personally and as our country as a whole. actually disgusted, furious and so god damn livid, that i was right. that's not something to enjoy being right about. a least i know. 2018 the year we can't afford the benefit of the doubt. #freepress #metoo #blacklivesmatter #waterprotectors #hospital #dontexpectmetoacceptthat #theresahateinfestation #2018 #america #notscaredofweakgenes #notappreciatingyourviolenthaterass #doesyourjesuscarryassaultriflestoo #theimagedoesntfitthewords #dontbeanazi #howhardisthat #valleypeoplehaventearnedrespectandwont #asfarasmyfriendssomehavealeopiechia #theresnothingracistorwrongwiithmybestfriend #whysthevalleysoshallow!

november 17, 12pm â€¢ the bronx museum 
1040 grand concourse, bronx, ny 
free event â€¢ workshops â€¢ panels â€¢ film â€¢ #mlc2018
keynote: nicole dennis-benn, writer/activist

the mlc2018 is a grassroots event and a great opportunity for the bronx and new york city communities of educators, students, program administrators, and parents to learn ways to integrate books and reading into the lives of teenagers. mlc offers a mix of informative programs and creative workshops to engage young minds, strengthen literacy, and develop education strategies.

130-230pm
#metoo & the movement
black women writers conjuring in the continuum 
in 2017, the #metoo campaign amplified the voices of survivors of rape, sexual assault and harassment. though social media platforms became the route to shared survivor stories, creating heightened awareness, accountability, and solidarity in response to a pervasive rape culture that is generations-deep, black women writers have courageously confronted patriarchal violence on the page while simultaneously experiencing a spectrum of abuses and violations in our personal lives. this panel, inspired by theÂ break beat poetsâ€™ black girl magic anthology, as well as other creative collaborations and alliances, will continue this urgently important conversation. through this community dialogue,we will explore the continuum of black women writing against all that would attempt to violate our lives. we will elevate our stories, our activism, our labor, and lineage. 
panelists: jp howard, keisha-gaye anderson, and diamond sharp. facilitator: nina angela mercer

this is a self portrait of my heart. 2018. .
this is how i love and where i love from. 
divinely comprised of my innocent younger-self, my bloodlines, my primordial ancestors. it is the moon and the earth and the cosmos. and my rage, my fear, my sadness, my longing... and my courage!! my "don't fuck with me" boundaries and protection.
.
this artwork is my very first #metoo disclosure - a story about rape and violence and sexual abuse and shame that i have been transforming for 20 years.
this is my stand for all those who cannot or will not stand.
.
i stand for you. .
this is my nervous system, and how it is nourished by my deeply loyal and tenacious heart. .
this is where i rest. in my strength. my having myself. my self-loving boundaries.
.
i created this whilst dancing the depths of my heart in a 3-day 5rhythms workshop. shedding the calcification and self-betrayal. transforming the collateral damage. a sacred ritual of retrieval of self. making amends, renewing my vows.

text:
weâ€™re married now, and i find myself thinking. the first time i set eyes on her, she was on the cover of a sports magazine, standing between two baseball players like me. i started collecting her pictures, and making contact with her image before i did with her flesh and blood. i had to have her. 
i knew what fame was and how dangerous it can be. and i knew fame would find her, tooâ€¦ but i had no idea what price fame would demand of her, and us. and i was not sure she knew, either.

yours, joe

text:
â€œel #oy esculturaâ€ (el hoy - eng. today) a new work by artist camila valdez @camilavaldezart â€”â€”â€”
manifiesto: 
the presence of the "#" hashtag symbol as a concept unifier and a social movement agent has culturally modified our way of communicating.

the hashtag has become a transforming symbol, where concepts like #metoo or #picoftheday flood our social networks with new meanings changing the way we perceive the world around us.

my artwork seeks to bring to light this fusion of the language itself, through the representation of characters in a mixed mess of letters which emerge from an ink spot, with the upper part being crowned by a hashtag symbol. all in helvetica typography which is socially the most chosen one for its balance and clearness

text:
i remember it as if it were yesterday. she sat across from me at dinner.
â€¢â€¢â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
i heard her talking about her day, about the drama, how she accomplished something new she had been working on for weeks.
â€¢â€¢â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
i was there physically however emotionally, i was somewhere else.
â€¢â€¢â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
i was numb.
â€¢â€¢â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
then the question came. â€œhow was your day?â€
â€¢â€¢â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
shaking my head nonchalantly i replied, â€œsame as yesterday.â€
â€¢â€¢â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
â€œreally? nothing new? what did you get done?â€ she asked.
â€¢â€¢â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
i had nothing.
â€¢â€¢â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
i had no recollection of what i had accomplished that day.
â€¢â€¢â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
my memory of what i had done just hours earlier at work was all a blur.
â€¢â€¢â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
she looked at me and i could see her yearning for connection, yearning for something, anything.
â€¢â€¢â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
and all i could do was shrug my shoulders.
â€¢â€¢â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
deep down inside, i knew i was dying.
â€¢â€¢â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
not physically dying, just emotionally flat lining.
â€¢â€¢â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
growing up, words of affirmation, words describing how i was feeling, was not something i ever practiced.
â€¢â€¢â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
the truth?
â€¢â€¢â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
i was about as emotionally out of shape as one could get and had no ability to share what i was experiencing inside emotionally. â€¢â€¢â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
what i didâ€™t realize at the time is that just like in anything, if you work at it, you can get stronger, more effective.
â€¢â€¢â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
it took years.
â€¢â€¢â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
tens of thousands of dollars in privates coaches, in personal development books, seminars, traveling the world seeking out how to become a more emotionally fit man.
â€¢â€¢â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
i see the #metoo movement and the call to men to up their game and i have seen the response.
â€¢â€¢â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
generally speaking, men have been silent.
â€¢â€¢â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
why? is it because men donâ€™t care? is it because weâ€™re not capable of stepping up?
â€¢â€¢â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
hell yes we care!
â€¢â€¢â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
it just takes time to strengthen the emotional fitness to the point where we can be confident to take on the responsibility of being great men.
â€¢â€¢â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
god knows society needs us to.
â€¢â€¢â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €

text:
thank the lord that not all cis-males are total pigs! ğŸ™ğŸ™ğŸ™ this is a platonic-friend of mine who i was talking to about my past with sexual abuse. he praised me about being body and sex positive with everything i've been through, and explained how he always asks a girl before even kissing her or holding their hand. (mind you, he is one of those guys who looks like a total "fuck boy".) and he's actually respectful! we need more people like this in the world!!!!! as much is at may seem weird or annoying, checking in on your sexual partners is actually a really important thing to do. even in a one night stand or a relationship/marriage. some people keep quiet about things they don't like, so it's good to give them the chance to open up about their wants/needs. especially because you never know what that person may have been through physically/mentally/emotionally/sexually before you.
examples you can use for reassurance:
"is this okay?"
"are you sure?"
"are you comfortable with this?"
"can i/may i?"

text:
sending #allthehighfives to today's #wednesdayfriendsday featured student, tatyana ragon! ğŸ‘
â€“â€“â€“â€“â€“â€“â€“â€“â€“â€“â€“â€“â€“â€“â€“â€“â€“â€“â€“â€“â€“â€“â€“â€“â€“
tatyana says she chose to start her college career at kent state stark because â€œit was close to home, and i am very family oriented. so it allowed me to see family more often.â€ she is now continuing her studies in the nursing program at kent state university.
â€“â€“â€“â€“â€“â€“â€“â€“â€“â€“â€“â€“â€“â€“â€“â€“â€“â€“â€“â€“â€“â€“â€“â€“â€“
tatyana is involved in the honors program and writes for honors scholars. this year alone, tatyana has been the lead organizer of two impactful events: the human trafficking awareness resource fair (march 2018) and the anti-human trafficking symposium (sept. 2018). she says, â€œlearning more about human trafficking â€“ and educating others who may not know a lot about it â€“ solidified what kind of nursing i want to do!â€ in the future, tatyana wants to work as a sane nurse that examines and cares for victims of sexual assault.
â€“â€“â€“â€“â€“â€“â€“â€“â€“â€“â€“â€“â€“â€“â€“â€“â€“â€“â€“â€“â€“â€“â€“â€“â€“
tonight, community members will hear from featured speaker mira sorvino - academy award-winning actress, silence breaker, anti-human trafficking activist and voice of the #metoo movement. tatyana is so excited to meet @mira sorvino and hear what she has to say. â€œi stand by what mira is advocating for â€“ i am proud to say i am a part of that movement of women standing up and speaking out about sexual assault and human trafficking. one in four women are sexually assaulted in their lifetime, and sometimes i look around when sitting in a classroom and wonder how many of my female classmates have been sexually assaulted. i am definitely a huge advocate for this movement.â€
â€“â€“â€“â€“â€“â€“â€“â€“â€“â€“â€“â€“â€“â€“â€“â€“â€“â€“â€“â€“â€“â€“â€“â€“â€“
if there is one thing tatyana could have told herself freshman year, it would be this: â€œyou do not have everything figured out! i changed my major several times and the best advice i would give anyone starting college is to be open minded to opening yourself up to all the opportunities that are out there.â€
â€“â€“â€“â€“â€“â€“â€“â€“â€“â€“â€“â€“â€“â€“â€“â€“â€“â€“â€“â€“â€“â€“â€“â€“â€“
fun fact: â€œi was adopted from russia with my two siblings when i was five years old!â€ says tatyana. â€œunfortunately, i forgot how to speak russian.â€ ğŸ˜‚

text: i'll never forget this moment as @ottilieclarke took this photo and started saying "hold the tension" and we both did not hold but completely collapsed into laughter. i feel really grateful to have such supportive and fun friends around me. people like ottilie and @xkimnn have truly been there and sat and listened through all my irrationality, my breakdowns and my hurt. 2 years ago they were both the only ones that really knew what had happened to me and what was going on. they were the ones walking alongside me and still are today. i wasn't in a good place and didn't want to talk about any of it. i assumed no one would believe me about the abuse that went on during my relationship since he had jumped and told everyone his version of events while i slipped into the background and left. i assumed no one would believe me about being raped because what evidence did i have. it's this mentality, this poisoning of our minds that lets people like this get away with it. after i finally told my parents about the abuse and rape i was asked if i wanted to prosecute either of them as we figured out that i did have enough evidence. however, i was ashamed and fearful back then. i sometimes wonder if i should have, was i a coward leaving them the opportunity to do it to someone else? maybe i am, you can make the judgement for yourself. however, i couldn't be more grateful for having those that have stood by me and dug deeper to look at the facts.

to my sexual assault/abuse survivor siblings who are trans: i see you. i celebrate your human beauty. i know your recovery is layered with additional weights i've not had to lift, and your journey takes you places i can try to understand, but i have not walked in your shoes. .
.
to those of us working to provide support and *serve* (and i really want us to think about that word) as allies to those who have been marginalized by lgbtqiap phobia, racism, colonization, sizeism, ablism, ageism, sexism, and other dangerous systemic biases, let's be extra thoughtful in our work. respect others' experiences and spaces - in the ways they want, need, and deserve. self educate. listen, learn, and practice... not just online, but in our daily lives. .
.
.
[image: white background with the words "trans is beautiful" in stylized type forming a rectangular shape in the center of the space.]
.
@thewordforthis

i hope that the #metoo campaign never loses steam; that we remember itâ€™s impact for all time. i hope that we can all dig deep and face the issue head-on. yes, itâ€™s uncomfortable.  but not one of us is outside this.  we are all accountable for our behaviors, past and present.
and if you are one who thinks this is #ascarytimeformen try #beingawoman

âœ· america ferrera âœ· actor, activist & now author! #vibrantwomen
.
america ferrera is known to most from movies & shows like ugly betty, sisterhood of the traveling pants & superstore. she's a golden globe winner and the first latina to win an emmy for best leading actress in a comedy, but apart from her career in entertainment, she's been very involved in politics as an activist throughout the years. in 2008 and 2016, she campaigned for hillary clinton and was a speaker at the 2016 dnc convention. america has worked with voto latino to help get latinos in the us to vote and was the opening speaker for the women's march in 2017. she took part in the #metoo campaign and was a founding member of the time's up legal defense fund after revealing her own story of sexual harassment. her latest work is an anthology of essays titled "american like me: reflections on life between cultures" featuring artists who write about what it means to be a multi-cultural american.

text:
in this video, i provide a verbal description of the method for calculating for reparations. a bit messy, this video showcases what @adriennemareebrown â˜”ï¸#adriennemareebrown calls an #emergentstrategy. this particular video draws attention to two people who were recently murdered by police. their families and #beloved communities miss them. may we #honor and #uplift the people who survive them, including you.

it usually takes me about 15 tries before i can teach the method with greatest #ease and spoken #eloquence. i'll be doing a series of videos on reparations focusing on such cases because, to me, they speak to the #horrors of this time as well as the various #beautiful possibilities we have for global #transformation. each video will show the further development of this free and open method for calculating reparations and showcase some of the ways i deploy #academic research to achieve my #sacred calling.

first, there is #no one method or formula for determining reparations. 
so much of the violence we experience is personalized. the violence we experience as individuals is always shared by other people and communities, yet how it affects us is embodied and related to who we are in this #earth walk. that's why this method was designed for people like you and #metoo.

second, calculating reparations is always an economic and spiritual practice.

above all, the #spiritual dimension of this method is central, and survivors must lead each initiative. the point is to foster healing, not pay for therapy and legal costs, and give people the support we require to create solutions for ourselves and our beloved communities. so, what does healing mean for you as a survivor of the violence you seek to stop? given your daily life and needs at this time, what do you need to put in place to learn and apply the method?

from a purely economic perspective, what aspects of healing can financial reparations facilitate? this question is the most direct, but it isn't as simple as it sounds. for example, you might #desire therapy and know that therapists cost a rate of, say $60-250 an hour. what if no therapist in your local #beloved community speaks your #wild tongue?
name: darshan elena campos

â€¢ iâ€™ve been following @loriharder for awhile and i find her to be beautiful, inspiring and the definition of an empowered woman ğŸ’ªğŸ» i love her stance on #girlpower and bringing women together in an authentically connected way ğŸ’•as we get older, we have less time & energy for fake, forced, or anything less than amazing relationships â€”  and so i think we could all benefit from loriâ€™s philosophy on a new way of being & a basic girl code to follow to be your best you in any situation â€¢â€¢ here is a brief description of the 7 sacred agreements in loriâ€™s book  #atribecalledbliss ~ about how to show up in your relationships & friendships in the most â€œauthentically-true to you, and the people you surround yourself withâ€ way ğŸ–¤ .
1) always be your own guru: trust yourself, value your voice above others who arenâ€™t walking in your shoes, â€œwhen you trust in yourself, you trust in the very wisdom that created you.â€ wayne dyer âœ¨ .
2) release expectations: see situations & people through a new lens, ask yourself what you could learn from each situation, donâ€™t expect - accept âœ¨
.
3) no gossip: itâ€™s one thing to talk about a situation in a healthy way to get your feelings out so that you can process, itâ€™s another thing to gossip about people behind their back â€¢â€¢ be a gossip killer and do not engage - â€œgreat minds discuss ideas, average minds discuss events, small minds discuss people.â€ eleanor roosevelt âœ¨
.
4) donâ€™t take it personal: â€œcare about what other people think and you will always be their prisoner.â€ lao tzu â€¢ remember itâ€™s never about you, it always about them truly, know that you will never make everyone happy, so just be you and let the rest go âœ¨ .
5) fierce boundaries: great boundaries are empowering, itâ€™s ok to say no, let go of the fear of it, and remember that boundaries make room for blessings âœ¨ .
6) be authentic: to be you feels like truth, to live your truth feels like bliss, the authentic you is bliss - itâ€™s that simple âœ¨
.
7) forgive yourself & everyone else: its ok to mess up, to fail & make mistakes, let it go & give it to god âœ¨ .
