text:
ğŸ’” rp @cristina_the_activist @fuck.your.excuses i snuck onto a noosa dairy farm yesterday. i wanted to see the babies with my own eyes. from afar it looked like the crates were empty but as i got closer and looked inside, there were day old babies huddled inside. it was 20 degrees out, had been snowing all night and here they were by themselves in the cold. so many of them were absolutely terrified of me - others would run up and start sucking on my fingers just hoping i was their mother.
some of them will be used in the dairy industry because they are considered profitable - others will be killed not too long from now so someone can eat their fragile body. 
this is animal agriculture.
it is not hard work, it is not a good job - it is selling your soul to profit off of others. 
it is separating families to make money off of their flesh. 
it is raping animals with your own two hands to keep their blood line going to keep your pockets full. 
it is mutilating babies and calling it normal and necessary. 
it is creating families, only to pull them apart.
the animal industry is nothing to glorify, it is nothing to be proud of. 
it is slavery and ultimately death.
this child does not belong here, but someone is paying to make this happen.. is it you?

text:
i left my underwear exposed to get former us president bill clintonâ€™s attention - monica lewinsky
.....
monica lewinsky concedes in a new documentary that she harbored a â€œcrushâ€ on president bill clinton throughout her early days at the white house, and frequently flirted with him â€” even intentionally leaving her underwear exposed on one occasion to get his attention.

at a 1995 birthday party for a white house staffer attended by the president, lewinsky realized that her underwear was protruding from the rear of her pants, she recalled in â€œthe clinton affair,â€ a new a&e documentary series. â€œinstead of pulling my trousers up, like i would in any other instance, i didnâ€™t,â€ said lewinsky. â€œit was unnoticeable to everybody else in the room, but [clinton] noticed.â€ â€œas i passed george stephanopoulosâ€™s office, i kind of looked into the open doorway,â€ she said. â€œand bill happened to be standing there. and he motioned me in, i donâ€™t think my heart had ever beat that fast. â€œunbeknownst to me, i was on the precipice of the rabbit hole.â€ lewinsky and clinton carried on a years long relationship into his second term in office, which came undone and ignited a national firestorm under the weight of the ken starr probe. â€œthere were always narratives of secrecy in this relationship,â€ lewinsky said. â€œwe were both cautious, but not cautious enough.â€ â€œi was completely at his mercy,â€ added lewinsky, who in recent years has penned essays re-examining the affair and authority clinton wielded in the light of the #metoo movement.

at the time, though, lewinsky said, the fling with the leader of the free world â€œjust felt like connecting.â€ â€œitâ€™s not as if it didnâ€™t register with me that he was the president,â€ lewinsky said. â€œobviously it did. but â€¦ the truth is, i think it meant more to me that someone who other people desired, desired me. however wrong it was â€¦ for who i was in that very moment, at 22 years old, that was how it felt.â€ the six-part series, produced by alex gibney and directed by blair foster, premieres on a&e at 9 p.m. sunday. ğŸ“¸: new york post

text:
such a great interview with john mayer because it's so true. soberity is so personal and we often forget it's an option. additionally he mentions the enabling on social media and how awkward it is to talk about because of the mixed reaction it gets. people are not always excited about someone else's sobriety and we often are unsure of how our friends will react. link in bio! 
i inspired one of my former colleagues to take a year off drinking and now he drinks very rarely and this last week was the first time i had seen him. he looked so healthy and happy yet could not be honest with his former colleagues about this decision and felt tons of peer pressure to drink and gave in one evening. it's so personal to so many people and as a society we need to be more accepting of someone's decision to say no thanks. my friend will be ok and the only result was a hangover but for someone like myself or my brother even one night out could result in something tragic and the brain will keep craving it.  it's a deadly and addictive drug and we forget that because of the marketing and popularity. 
i am obsessed with @johnmayer and went to see him live when i was in treatment. his songs helped me get through the hardest thing in my entire life and i am so grateful for him. i am so happy to hear he has stuck with it! sobriety is such a special club to be a part of ğŸ’“

text:
the 3rd oil in the starter kit is digize vitality! i could not think of anything cute to add to this picture but that does not mean i love this oil any less than the others. this oil is absolutely amazing for everything digestion, obviously!
digize is a blend of tarragon, ginger, peppermint, juniper, fennel, lemongrass,  anise, and patchouli. i will not lie when you pull this out of your kit and smell it you are going to want to put it right back. ğŸ¤£ that being said our favorite ways to use this one is in a circular  motion around your belly button or inside a veggie capsule. donâ€™t let the smell deter you because it is seriously a life saver when it comes to tummy troubles, hence the smiley face on the chalkboard ğŸ˜‚. my husband is lactose intolerant and refuse to give up cheese, how could you blame him? so when he eats dairy he uses this oil to relieve him. it is also great for when you feel cruddy after overindulging or eating fast food. ğŸ¤¢ you can also pair it with peppermint, which you guessed it comes in the starter kit, for even more support.
diffusing digize can help when you are feeling squeamish or queezy. you can diffuse it with peppermint to again intensify relief but it will also cut the fennel smell. it is also creates a relaxing atmosphere when diffused. if you have kiddos try the diluted version for kids tummygize! 
what is your fave way to use digize? .
.
.

text:
my first novel won the 2016 new apple awards medal for general fiction and was endorsed by marideth sisco who worked with the oscar nominated film "winter's bone" starring jennifer lawrence. .
.
lovella is a rebellious and promiscuous girl growing up in the 1960's. she thinks she knows everything, and wants out of her small town life, away from her controlling mother. however, when she meets an ugly hippie she starts learning lessons about life she had never even considered, and she learns a truth about herself and her mother that she never knew existed.
.
.
read the first three chapters on the blog page of my website at karlyletomms.com
.
.

text:
the serious issue here is the language used by the prime minister of australia, in relation to his buddies accompanying him to meet with pamela anderson.

i donâ€™t care for the comments made by pamela in regards to the #metoo movement and i care even less for julian assange and his issues. 
what i do care about is the tone of the pmâ€™s comment and meaning behind it.

is she inviting you to a meet and greet for her latest playboy spread? 
no. 
regardless of any womanâ€™s past and her choices, this type of comment is exactly way the #metoo movement started. 
how are we meant to educate young boys into  men when you have the leader of our australian government promoting this culture?

for any males out there that donâ€™t â€œget thisâ€ or understand the fuss, sit down and ask a female close to you this question; â€œhave you ever felt uncomfortable by a sexual innuendo made by a male in a professional environment?â€ sticks and stones may break my bones but words will never hurt me?

one manâ€™s â€œinnocentâ€ comment is another manâ€™s â€œinnocentâ€ rub of your shoulders while sit at your desk trying to do your work.

i have some beautiful males in my life and not everyone needs to be tarred with the same brush, i just wish our pm would set a better example and not creep into trump territory.

written by lorelie rozzano

dear reader,

substance use disorder is a disease that affects one in seven families. many think addiction is a singular illness, meaning only the addicted person gets sick. however, that has not been my experience. as the daughter of an alcoholic and working in the field of mental health and addiction these past 18 years, iâ€™ve come to understand we are all equally affected. 
you may find some passages in this book shocking. you might wonder 'is this true?' although i have changed the names and events, rest assured, in addicted families, scenes like the ones youâ€™re about to read play out every day.
may the jagged series give you the glasses you need to see clearly; addiction is a family illness. i hope you find the strength and courage to reach out for help. please know the only way you can fail at recovery is to quit trying. 
much love, 
lorelie rozzano.

text: how it is, ep. 2: the gray area. (24 minutes).Â the issues that matter most are never simple. journalist and jezebel founder anna holmes discusses the online outrage culture that drowns out nuance (and her own role in creating it); writer kayla whaley explains her longing to be catcalled (even though she doesnâ€™t want to be harassed); and comedianÂ jenny yang embraces her complexity (while she sometimes feels guilty for it). hosted by diane guerrero. brought to you by reese witherspoon and hello sunshine. the discussion about outrage culture, and how it limits nuance, was so interesting. it is so easy these days to get up in arms about everything. sometimes it's hard to know where to draw the line. and to think that some of the people who helped to create it might regret it. the discussion of the gray area of the #metoo movement (which i can pretty much guarantee is not the gray area you think it is) was simultaneously repellant and totally relatable. #howitispodcast #howitis #thegrayarea #culturepodcast #podcast #whatimlisteningto #earjams

text:
